        9th March 2024

        OK, so no else has mentioned it yet but a milestone at #61 as the The Killers rack up a record 400 weeks on the Top 100 chart. Orginally charting on 5 June 2004 at its peak of 10, it has spent only 147 of those 400 weeks in the Top 75. Which isn't brilliant to be honest. They have much better songs, but given Mr. B is the lead track on their 2013 greatest hits album, it probably picks up more streams than other tracks that way.

        Next in the longevity stakes is Lewis Capaldi's Someone You Loved at 227 Top 100 weeks and given that was a 2018 new entry, and spent 157 weeks in the Top 75 (69%), and 7 weeks at #1, I'd say this was an overall better showing.

        Chart Review 08/03/24

        Man, the BRITs were uneventful, weren't they? I mean, there I was, on Saturday night, trying to explain to my mum why the likes of Bring Me The Horizon were worthy of overcoming The Rolling Stones, and having to come to terms with the fact that underground rapper CASISDEAD has more BRITs than Radiohead, Jamiroquai and BTS. I mean, crikey, I've barely heard of that guy, and there he is on that stage, more worthy of an award than Dave, Central Cee and J Hus. Look, there's being eccentric with your voting, and then there's spinning a wheel and picking whatever name it lands on. Given you couldn't go 5 minutes without RAYE tearing up onstage, it probably makes less sense than it should.

        I guess that's why the singles chart looks as dead as it usually turns out to be, even though there's a knee-slapping 3 new hits of varying levels of successful musicianship, naturally none of which is enough to dislodge Queen B from the summit. You can clock that up as 3 weeks at the summit for TEXAS HOLD 'EM, but given Benson Boone's just overtaken her on the Spotify chart, her days are starting to get a little numbered. I just wish they weren't. You don't know disappointment until your favourite tune of the moment is overlapped at just the wrong time of year, by the worst tune you can imagine without strangling your descendants for streaming it. Fun fact: I still haven't heard the Benson Boone tune in full. Can you blame me?

        Er... what else has happened, um... Kanye West is in the Top 5, so I guess he'll be having some fiestas soon I presume. His first Top 5 smash since that one in 2018 with the Roblox people and the somewhat sexual imagery. You know, T H A T one. The one that goes, I LOVE IT. Come on, I thought you knew it off by heart by now. Ah well. Oh, and Alibi by Ella Henderson is in the best-sellers now. I'd post you how disappointed I am at the British public for letting this happen, but you sadly can't put pictures on the OCC website. Then again, back when you could, the Disqus system made their signing in logic so strenuous it frazzled by puny little cranium. What was I saying? Oh right. Stop giving Ella Henderson love. Or else.

        Elsewhere, and RAYE is goated, if the BRITs were anything to go by. Just the SIX awards given to Rachel Agatha Keen for her My 21st Century Blues opus, as RAYE read the Stormzy Official Licensed guide to independent success and wtched the money roll in. This naturally means that former chart-topper and four minute TikTok graverobber Escapism. shoots back to 13 in its first Top 40 appearance since that wonderous time of, erm, May 2023. Even though co-star 070 Shake has had as much prowess since then as I've had posting these reviews. Of a more noteworthy comment, though, and the resulting success sees a song cruelly ignored in the past breach the 40 for the first time. Step forward, album highlight Worth It.. (I intended to put two full stops there. All the songs on her album have those comatose sentence stoppers, and it kills the mood a little.) Played to death on Radio 1 at the end of 2023, and the public received it warmly by not streaming it at all. Given the only other song from her album, Flip A Switch., barely grazed the Top 40, this is slightly objective from her audience. Ah well. We can remove any lingering doubts now as Worth It. breaks its way to 38, a position it should've gotten months ago. Now make some new music already RAYE, I'm still somewhat judging you on the basis that your album got stopped by Shania Twain a year ago.

        Her album doesn't top the charts now either, only able to fly up to No.5, as the latest seven-day wonder at the top are Oasis stalwart Liam Gallagher and Stone Roses axeman John Squire, who predictably sail to the summit with their self-titled collaborative album, a far cry from the days when John's second album reached the whopping heights of 90 some twenty years prior. Lead single Just Another Rainbow, of course, fell from 16 to NOWHERE back in January, proof that physical sales don't get you anywhere in the long-term, but you know, the album's alright, even though I bet barely any of the 40,000 buyers hail from outside the North West. Now, as a Mancunian myself, I am slightly gutted that Everything Everything's latest behemoth, Mountainhead only got 9, primarily because lead single Cold Reactor is one of, if not the best thing you'll hear all year. This could be the song to stop The Last Dinner Party in my Fab 50 countdown at the end of the year. But I'm getting ahead of myself...

        I haven't talked about him that much in recent weeks, probably becuase there's not much to say, but Michael Marcagi is now in the Top 20, and I am officially campaigning for him to get out as soon as possible. Just need to remove One Of The Girls, Prada, Lil Boo Thang and Whatever first, and then we'll talk, Mikey. Pozer's up one, so clearly no one forgot about him, and Bryson Tiller can also be found in the 20 best-sellers, again, a song that doesn't do much outside of soundtrack 17 year old Chevrolets from San Francisco. And not the good Chevrolets, either.

        As for the ACTUAL new hits, No.26 sees the return of music's great underachiever, Charli XCX. It's been a decade since she popped up on that Icona Pop song which hit the top, then had big success with Boom Clap and Doing It, but seems to have ended up as one of the most overhyped artists ever since. Everyone loves her, apart from the charts it seems. Album topped the chart in 2022, lead single doesn't make the Top 20. Fab 50 pop-up and Sam Smith collab In The City struggled to 41, yet her Barbie contribution Speed Drive went Top 10. Her lack of success is one of life's great mysteries, alongside the omnipresence of Ed Sheeran and why her debut single in 2008 was called !Franchesckaar!. Anyways, she's back, and she's at least in the 40 this time with von dutch, even though she makes some rather ambitious claims in the chorus. "I'm your number one", she utters. In your imagination, maybe. Right now she's 25 places lower, so she may be forever stuck as a critical darling until the cows come home. And I think the bovines are starting to pull up outside my house.

        The other new entry on show is down at 34, and after 8 years of providing the soundtrack of 2016 (along with the usual suspects, as 2016 was the WORST year for music in a long time), Twenty One Pilots are finally back. Admittedly yes, they have made music in that intervening period, but after Level Of Concern stiffed at 43 in 2020, you could make a bold claim that they were never coming back. That claim is well and truly shattered, if Overcompensate is anything to go by, a song that just doesn't sound like Top 40 material in this day and age, given it's more reminiscent of HYAENA by Travis Scott if anything. But I loved HYAENA, so naturally I've taken this song to heart. Their first Top 40 hit since Suicide Squad song Heathens went Top 5, and their album Clancy is out in May. Buy it, off the back of this single alone.

        Outside the 40, and it's looking grim for the UK's Eurovision chances, if Olly Alexander's Dizzy is anything to go by. Not only because the song is so mid I have trouble remembering a single part of it, but because it's entered at miserly 42. Come on, Olly, why can't you be like Ireland? Or Croatia? Or Finland? At the very least, you could've made it not sound like 60% of your back catalogue. No.46 sees Miley Cyrus collab with Pharrell Williams, and given the chart position it seems that no one wanted it to happen, nor cared. Richy Mitch & The Coalminers are at 41 for some reason, FE!N by Travis Scott has now risen to 47, Skrapz, Nines and D-Block Europe are at 51, Fred Again.. could've done better with his new one, a Kanye album track charts for the first time at 100, and No.92 sees Myles Smith enter the public consciousness. Shame he sounds like David Kushner.

        Next week sees everyone fold up their baskets and go home to watch Celebrity Big Brother, as Ariana Grande's just released seventh album Eternal Sunshine, so expect at least 2 Top 10 smashes in the form of yes, and?, and whatever else takes the listeners' affection. Mazza_l20 returns off the back of surprise Top 20 hit Murdaside, but given he's a serial offender I don't think he'll be having hits for a good while, Drake has popped up on a remix of Spotify underachiever act ii: date @ 8 by 4batz, so expect that to do something, Clavish is back, d4vd returns, Norah Jones and Judas Priest attempt to stop the Ariana juggernaut, Nina Nesbitt is back to impress nobody, and FLO are back with new music for the first time since that Fly Girl schtick in 2023 which reached No.38. Given they've been lapped several times in the BBC Sound Of affections by The Last Dinner Party, they'll need to spice up their lives and make some brill sounds. So obviously their new one sounds like Fly Girl Part 2. There goes the love for you girls, I guess.

        I'm off to do nothing for 7 days. And finally, as Welsh band Helen Love once sang in 1998, Long Live The UK Music Scene. Too-da-loo.



        (P.S. I would've posted my Top 20 analysis on Sunday, but the website was having a hissy-fit. At least you haven't made a shambles of the Top 100 this week, right OCC?)
